IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
The incident was captured via I-24 in car camera and body warn cameras of units on scene.

Scene Processing:
Statements from suspects and victim were collected on scene. Photo documentation of the scene was completed. All firearms were seized in addition to a spent shell casing located on the victim’s vehicle. The CCTV on scene was not operational.

Neighborhood Checks:
Due to the nature of the incident, no neighborhood checks were completed.

Narrative:
On 7/23/2023, at approximately 2222 hours, I, TFC Cambra #7191 was dispatched to 12041 Cordova Rd, Cordova Maryland for a reported robbery in progress. While enroute, I was advised by the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack that the caller, identified as Mark William Lillard (11/22/1983), had two subjects detained. Upon arrival, I observed a entrance with multiple locked gates and no lights. I advised the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack that there was no one near the front of the property.
I began to drive around the area to attempt to locate the caller. While searching with other units, the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack advised us they were at the back of the property and it needed to be access by traveling down Coveys Landing Rd, then an access road to the rear of the property.
Upon arrival, I observed two subjects on the ground which were detained by the Talbot County Sheriff’s Office Deputies. The subjects on the ground were later identified as William Alvan Moore 3rd (DOB: 05/18/1997 2/M) and Paul Thomas Swann Jr (DOB:09/01/1999 2/M). A moment later, I was advised there were three additional subjects inside of the building. An additional unit and myself opened the closed door to the building and immediately located three subjects against the wall with their hands out in front of them. The subjects were detained and removed from the building. The subjects that were inside were identified as Quinn Addison Worm (DOB: 08/06/2004 2/F), Carson Reeve George (DOB: 07/17/2004 2/M), and Morgan Bailey Smith (DOB: 10/19/2000 2/F).
I made contact with Lillard who stated the following:
  • Arrived at the address earlier in the day, workers dropped off a scissor lift.
  • The gate was open
  • He advised his employees that he was staying at the location for the evening.
  • Went to the Royal Farms down the street and came back to find suspects at the location
  • “two guys run at me like they are gonna fuckin do something”
  • Ordered them to the ground
  • They were here to steel copper
Lillard advised Moore and Swann exited the building from the door directly to the side of the victim’s car.
            There was a white Chevy Silverado with a utility bed parked at the end of the driveway. The Silverado had Maryland registration 36737K. I made contact with Swann. A MVA check of the vehicle revealed the truck is registered to Paul Thomas Swann Jr. While peering into Swann’s vehicle, I observed a black Savage Bolt action rifle resting near the center console of the truck near the front passenger seat. A check of the gun revealed one round to be in the chamber with additional rounds in the magazine. While checking the firearm, Swann advised the firearm was registered to him. A closer inspection of the rifle revealed it to be a Savage B Mag (Serial Number N644899) chambered in 17 Winchester Super Magnum. A box of 28 Gauge shotgun ammunition was located in the front passenger door, and additional ammunition for the 17 Winchester Super Magnum was located on top of the center console.
            Swann stated the following:
  • A local farmer tills and seeds the fields outside.
  • They thought it would be cool to see the inside of the building
  • The gate was open when they arrived, the doors to the building were “
    wide open”
  • They had never been back there and they wanted to check it out
  • There were there for maybe 5 minutes before law enforcement
  • The Victim was yelling at them various things to include
    • Who’s in there
  • They came out of the door out of respect and it went to far
  • The victim had them at gun point and they didn’t have the opportunity to speak
I made contact with Moore who advised stated the following:
  • They rode up there to see it because they thought Mark Stump owned it
  • They were not steeling anything
  • They were there for maybe 20 minutes before the incident
  • They walked up, walked up the steps, looked at the tanks
  • That guy (Victim) was yelling
  • The victim shot, presumably in the air, 1 or 2 rounds not directed t hem
  • Saw the firearm to be a handgun

I made contact with Carson Reeve George who stated the following:
  • Riding back in the field
  • Thought the farmer that tills the fields owned the building
  • “Wernt doin nothing, no harm”
  • Saw open gate when he arrived
  • Doesn’t want to steal anyone
  • The two other females, and him stayed inside while the two others exited to meet with the person who arrived
  • They the victim shoot and they believed someone got shot so they stayed inside
  • He was sure it was a gunshot
  • They were there for maybe 15 minutes before anyone arrived

Another unit recovered a firearm from the victim’s vehicle. The firearm was found to be a black polymer Springfield XDM 9mm (Serial Number MG906381).
            I made contact with Swann again who stated the following:
  • The victim was standing by his vehicle driver side door, the firearm was pointed over them and shot once or twice

I was advised by additional unit on scene that the victim admitted to “firing a warning shot”. I made contact with the victim again, and advised him that I was told he fired a warning shot which he agreed. He stated it was a single warning shot pointed in the air over the building. A search of the area resulted in the recovery of one spent shell casing located on the roof of the victims vehicle near the trunk.
            All of the suspects on scene were arrested and transported to the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack for processing. I asked the victim if he would be willing to complete a written statement which he declined and preferred the verbal statements made.
            I requested a tow truck for the suspect’s vehicle, the white Chevrolet Silverado
           

All suspects were ultimately removed from the building and detained. One of the subjects that was outside the building upon my arrival was identified as William, Alvan Moore 3rd (DOB: 05/18/1997).

A search of the property revealed the gate to the property was open, however, there was one “no trespassing” signs on each of the gates with two total signs. Lillard advised me Moore exited the building when he arrived. Moore was subsequently arrested and transported to the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack for processing. I observed signs on the fence that was open to say “No Trespassing”. Each gate had a sign on it. I took possession of the victims firearm and ammunition and the spend shell casing. I took possession of the suspects Savage Rifle and ammunition. I requested a tow truck for the suspect vehicle. I took photo documentation of the compartments of the truck which contained a plethora of power tools and miscellaneous equipment. Knotts towing arrived on scene and removed the white Silverado.

The victim was provided a victim pamphlet. I contacted the Maryland State Police Gun Center in relation to Swann’s firearm. The gun center advised Swann was not prohibited and there were no recommended charges listed. All recovered items were processed as per department policy and regulation.

 
All events occurred in Talbot County, Maryland.
